  ep3: {
    A1: {
      outcome: 'You model the step-by-step process and ask all students to redo Q1. 22 of 24 students now show a process, up from 12. Nur adds the equation step. Rajan sighs and writes the steps he already knew. Siti follows the model carefully. The processes are now visible — but they are uniform, and you cannot tell who understood and who copied.',
      tradeoff: 'The reteach makes the process visible for almost everyone. But it homogenises the variety of methods in the room and may have replaced genuine reasoning with procedural compliance.',
      reflection: 'Describe: You modelled the step-by-step process and asked students to redo the question. Almost all students now show working.\n\nCompare: A process reteach is efficient at making thinking visible — but it standardises the method rather than revealing the range of approaches students were using. AQS peer feedback might have surfaced more genuine reasoning.\n\nCritical: What is the difference between showing working and understanding the process? How do you design tasks that make genuine reasoning visible rather than just compliance?'
    },
    A2: {
