      tradeoff: 'Peer feedback surfaces more genuine reasoning than a whole-class reteach. But Siti is receiving rather than producing, and the feedback quality varies across pairs.',
      reflection: 'Describe: You used AQS peer feedback to surface and improve the hidden methods. Some pairs made real gains.\n\nCompare: AQS peer feedback is more personalised than a whole-class reteach — but it requires students to have a method to share. Students with no visible process need a different entry point.\n\nCritical: How do you design for students who have correct answers but no visible process? What does it mean to "show your thinking" — and how do you make that expectation clear from the start?'
    },
    B1: {
      outcome: 'You run the IRF probe. Wei Jie explains why Step 2 is written as an equation — "because you need to know what the missing angle equals." A second student builds on it. A third evaluates. Rajan, who skipped the scaffold, listens with interest. Siti is called on and freezes — she cannot explain the step she copied.',
      tradeoff: 'The IRF probe deepens the reasoning of the students who used the scaffold genuinely. But it exposes Siti\'s copying and puts her in a difficult position publicly.',
      reflection: 'Describe: You used an IRF chain to probe the reasoning behind the scaffold steps. The chain produced a strong class-built explanation.\n\nCompare: IRF probing after scaffolding is a powerful way to test genuine understanding — but it can expose students who were copying rather than reasoning. A private check-in with Siti before the probe might have been kinder.\n\nCritical: How do you use scaffolds in a way that builds genuine understanding rather than just procedural compliance? What is the scaffold for — and when do you remove it?'
    },
    B2: {
      outcome: 'Students attempt the new triangle without the scaffold. Rajan completes it quickly with clear steps. Nur attempts it and gets the right answer but skips the equation step again. Wei Jie works through it carefully and gets it right. Siti writes the angles and stops — without the scaffold structure, she does not know what to do next.',
      tradeoff: 'Scaffold removal tests genuine internalisation. Rajan and Wei Jie have internalised the process; Nur and Siti have not. You now have clear evidence — but less time to respond.',
      reflection: 'Describe: You removed the scaffold to test transfer. The responses revealed who had genuinely internalised the process and who had been relying on the structure.\n\nCompare: Scaffold removal is a necessary step — but timing matters. Removing support before understanding is consolidated can undo the gains made. Nur and Siti needed more time with the scaffold.\n\nCritical: How do you know when a student is ready to work without a scaffold? What evidence would tell you it is too soon — and what would you do differently next time?'
    },
    C1: {
      outcome: 'Four method comparisons are posted. The class gives AQS feedback on the weakest one — a pair that wrote "same method, both correct." Several students affirm the correct answer. Nur questions what the method actually was. A third student suggests writing the equation step. The feedback is specific. The 10 mirroring pairs look at the posted responses and realise their own comparisons were shallow.',
      tradeoff: 'The AQS gallery critique makes the difference between genuine and superficial comparison visible to the whole class. But the mirroring pairs may feel exposed, and Siti has nothing posted.',
      reflection: 'Describe: You used the gallery talk output as the basis for AQS feedback. The critique revealed the difference between genuine and superficial method comparison.\n\nCompare: AQS on gallery responses is more concrete than general feedback — but it requires students to have produced something worth critiquing. The mirroring pairs needed a more structured prompt to produce genuine comparisons.\n\nCritical: How do you design pair tasks so that students compare genuinely rather than confirm each other? What would the task need to say to produce real method comparison?'
    },
    C2: {
      outcome: 'Students draw or write their personal method for Q4 individually. Rajan writes a clear, efficient method. Nur writes the correct numbers but no equation. Wei Jie draws a diagram with all steps labelled. Siti writes the angles and the answer — no process. The individual maps give you honest evidence of each student\'s thinking.',
      tradeoff: 'The solo process maps give you the clearest picture of each student\'s thinking. But the move to individual work has stopped the emerging talk, and Siti\'s map reveals that the pair work did not help her.',
      reflection: 'Describe: You asked students to map their personal method individually. The responses gave you honest evidence of each student\'s thinking process.\n\nCompare: Individual process maps are the most honest measure of hidden thinking — but they work best when students have had time to develop a method worth mapping. The pair talk may not have given Siti enough to work with.\n\nCritical: What does it mean to have a "method" in mathematics? How do you help students who arrive at correct answers through intuition or guessing to develop an explicit, transferable process?'
    }
  }
