      tradeoff: 'The IRF probe bridges verbal understanding and calculation meaning for the students who respond. But Siti is publicly exposed as unable to make the connection.',
      reflection: 'Describe: You used an IRF chain to bridge verbal understanding and calculation meaning. The chain produced a strong policy connection.\n\nCompare: IRF probing is powerful for deepening understanding — but it can expose LS students who are still at the verbal stage. A private check-in before the probe might have given Siti a way in.\n\nCritical: How do you use whole-class discussion in a way that includes LS students rather than exposing them? What structures would make the IRF chain more equitable?'
    },
    B2: {
      outcome: 'Students attempt the new data set without the formula strip. Rajan completes it with a policy recommendation. Nur attempts the calculation and gets it right — the formula strip seems to have helped. Wei Jie gets the calculation partially right but cannot write the policy implication. Siti writes the verbal explanation and stops at the calculation.',
      tradeoff: 'Scaffold removal tests genuine transfer. Nur has internalised the formula; Wei Jie and Siti have not. You have clear evidence — but less time to respond.',
      reflection: 'Describe: You removed the scaffold to test transfer. Nur demonstrated genuine internalisation; Wei Jie and Siti have not yet made the connection.\n\nCompare: Scaffold removal is a necessary step — but timing matters. Wei Jie and Siti needed more time with the formula strip before being asked to work without it.\n\nCritical: How do you know when an LS student is ready to work without a scaffold? What evidence would tell you it is too soon — and what would you do differently?'
    },
    C1: {
      outcome: 'Three pairs share their verbal-to-calculation bridges. The class gives AQS feedback. Several students affirm the verbal explanations. Nur questions one pair\'s calculation link and suggests connecting the number to the policy implication. Wei Jie takes notes. Siti copies the feedback from the board.',
      tradeoff: 'The AQS feedback makes the verbal-calculation bridge visible and concrete. But the 8 verbal-only pairs are still receiving rather than producing, and Siti is copying rather than reasoning.',
      reflection: 'Describe: You used AQS feedback on shared verbal-to-calculation bridges. The feedback made the connection between verbal understanding and calculation explicit.\n\nCompare: AQS on real student work is more concrete than general feedback — but it requires students to have made the connection first. The 8 verbal-only pairs needed a more structured prompt to produce a bridge.\n\nCritical: How do you design tasks that help LS students move from verbal understanding to calculation — without making the calculation feel like a separate, harder task?'
    },
    C2: {
      outcome: 'Students calculate PED individually and write a policy recommendation. Rajan writes a nuanced recommendation with caveats. Nur calculates correctly and writes a basic recommendation. Wei Jie calculates partially and writes "the firm should raise price" without justification. Siti writes the verbal explanation and leaves the calculation blank.',
      tradeoff: 'Individual evidence reveals the full range of understanding. But the move to solo work has left Siti without the verbal scaffolding of her partner, and the calculation gap remains.',
      reflection: 'Describe: You moved from pair talk to individual application. The responses revealed the full range of verbal-to-calculation understanding.\n\nCompare: Individual application is the most honest measure of whether the bridge has been built — but it works best when the collaborative phase has genuinely helped students make the connection.\n\nCritical: For LS students who understand verbally but struggle with calculation, what is the right sequence of support? How do you design a lesson that builds the bridge rather than just testing whether it exists?'
    }
  }
};

